{{ill|Kagoshima Gokoku Shrine|ja|鹿児島県護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (鹿児島県護国神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Gokoku Shrine|ja|護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) located in Kusumuda 2-chōme, {{ill|Kagoshima City|ja|鹿児島市|lt=Kagoshima City|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|ja|鹿児島県|lt=Kagoshima Prefecture|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan.. It is a [[Beppyo shrine]], or a shrine that is particularly notable in a certain way with a significant history to it.<ref>{{Cite web |title=別表神社とは？御朱印めぐりに参考になる「別表神社一覧」とマップ {{!}} 開運戦隊ゴシュインジャー |url=https://jinja-gosyuin.com/beppyou/ |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=jinja-gosyuin.com}}</ref> It is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]], or a shrine dedicated to war dead.{{Efn|Is this [[WP:BLUE]] considering that the shrine is literally named as such?}} Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the war dead, and they were all considered "branches" of [[Yasukuni Shrine]]. They were renamed from [[Shōkonsha|Shokonsha]] in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

== deity Enshrined ==
The shrine enshrines over 77,000 spirits from Kagoshima Prefecture who perished in service to the nation since the [[Meiji Restoration]]: including those who died in national crises, Self-Defense Forces personnel who died in the line of duty, as well as police officers and firefighters who lost their lives serving the public.

== History ==
In Meiji 1 (1868), utilizing 500 ryō of gold granted by Emperor Meiji to honor those who fell in the {{ill|Battle of Toba–Fushimi|ja|鳥羽・伏見の戦い|lt=Toba-Fushimi War|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the shrine was first established as the '''Isetamareisha (靖献霊社)'''. Initially, it stood to the right side of {{ill|Terukuni Shrine|ja|照国神社|lt=Terukuni Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (currently, near the Boshin parking area). In Meiji 8 (1875), it was renamed "Kagoshima Shōkonsha," and in Shōwa 14 (1939), it took the name "Kagoshima-ken Gokoku Jinja."

After World War II, in Shōwa 22 (1947), to avoid being abolished as a militaristic facility, it was temporarily renamed "Satsugū Shōtoku Jinja" (薩隅頌徳神社). The following year (Shōwa 23), it was relocated to its current location, and in Shōwa 26 (1951), it reverted to its current name. In April Heisei 19 (2007), a statue commemorating Special Attack Force heroes (Tokkō Yūshi) was erected on the grounds.

== Surroundings ==
* {{ill|Kagoshima Prefectural Kagoshima Technical High School|ja|鹿児島県立鹿児島工業高等学校|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is located opposite the shrine. Before the school’s own archery range (dōjō) was completed, its archery club used the Gokoku Shrine’s archery range.

